üîß FIGMA MAKE UPDATE PROMPT ‚Äì Stock Inventory workflow (Stock Overview)

You are extending the Stock Overview feature in
‚ÄúLe Comptoir Stock Management‚Äù by adding a full inventory workflow.

This feature must be clear, guided, and auditable.
Do not simplify. Do not omit any step.

‚∏ª

1) Stock Overview ‚Äì New inventory entry points

1.1 Add ‚ÄúStart inventory‚Äù action

In the Stock Overview section:
	‚Ä¢	Add a visible button: Start inventory
	‚Ä¢	This button is global to the Stock Overview (not per category)

Near this button, also add:
	‚Ä¢	A secondary button: Inventory history

Both buttons must be clearly visible and accessible.

‚∏ª

2) Start inventory ‚Äì Configuration modal

Clicking Start inventory opens a modal to configure the inventory scope.

2.1 Inventory scope selection (mandatory)

In the modal, allow the user to configure:
	‚Ä¢	Hardware category (mandatory, single selection)
	‚Ä¢	Example: Workstation, Mobile, Headset
	‚Ä¢	Only one category can be inventoried at a time
	‚Ä¢	Model selection (optional, within the selected category)
	‚Ä¢	Options:
	‚Ä¢	All models
	‚Ä¢	One specific model
	‚Ä¢	Multiple selected models (checkbox list)

These fields must be:
	‚Ä¢	Clickable
	‚Ä¢	Clearly explained
	‚Ä¢	Validated before proceeding

‚∏ª

2.2 Inventory start action

Actions in the modal:
	‚Ä¢	Cancel
	‚Ä¢	Start inventory

Starting the inventory opens the inventory scanning view.

‚∏ª

3) Inventory scanning view (core workflow)

3.1 Inventory context display

At the top of the inventory screen, display:
	‚Ä¢	Selected category
	‚Ä¢	Selected model(s)
	‚Ä¢	Inventory status (In progress)

‚∏ª

3.2 Expected items list

The system must display:
	‚Ä¢	The list of expected items (equipment supposed to be present)
	‚Ä¢	Based on:
	‚Ä¢	Selected category
	‚Ä¢	Selected models
	‚Ä¢	Current stockroom

Each expected item shows:
	‚Ä¢	Barcode
	‚Ä¢	Model
	‚Ä¢	Status:
	‚Ä¢	Not scanned
	‚Ä¢	Scanned (found)

‚∏ª

3.3 Scanning behavior

When scanning equipment:

Case 1 ‚Äì Expected item
	‚Ä¢	Mark item as Found
	‚Ä¢	Update status in the list

Case 2 ‚Äì Unexpected item
	‚Ä¢	Item is not expected in this inventory scope
	‚Ä¢	Display it in a separate section:
	‚Ä¢	Unexpected items found
	‚Ä¢	Highlight visually

‚∏ª

4) Inventory completion & summary

4.1 Inventory summary screen

When the user finishes scanning and clicks Complete inventory, display a summary showing:
	‚Ä¢	Total expected items
	‚Ä¢	Items found
	‚Ä¢	Items missing (expected but not scanned)
	‚Ä¢	Items unexpected (scanned but not expected)

This distinction is mandatory.

‚∏ª

4.2 Inventory validation

Actions:
	‚Ä¢	Cancel (return to scanning)
	‚Ä¢	Validate inventory

Once validated:
	‚Ä¢	Inventory is closed
	‚Ä¢	Results are saved
	‚Ä¢	No further modification possible

‚∏ª

5) Stock Overview ‚Äì Inventory indicators

5.1 Inventory freshness per model

In the Stock Overview list, for each model:
	‚Ä¢	Display ‚ÄúDays since last inventory‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Example: ‚Äú12 days ago‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Do NOT display exact dates
	‚Ä¢	This value updates after each validated inventory

This indicator must be:
	‚Ä¢	Visible
	‚Ä¢	Readable
	‚Ä¢	Useful for operational follow-up

‚∏ª

6) Inventory history

6.1 Inventory history access

Clicking Inventory history opens a modal displaying:
	‚Ä¢	List of past inventories
	‚Ä¢	Ordered from most recent to oldest

Each inventory entry shows:
	‚Ä¢	Category
	‚Ä¢	Model(s)
	‚Ä¢	Inventory date
	‚Ä¢	Summary:
	‚Ä¢	Found / Missing / Unexpected counts

‚∏ª

6.2 Inventory details

Clicking an inventory entry opens a detail view showing:
	‚Ä¢	Full list of:
	‚Ä¢	Expected items
	‚Ä¢	Found items
	‚Ä¢	Missing items
	‚Ä¢	Unexpected items
	‚Ä¢	Clear separation between each group

This view is read-only.

‚∏ª

7) Roles & permissions (important)
	‚Ä¢	Inventory actions are available to:
	‚Ä¢	Campus role
	‚Ä¢	Central Stock Manager
	‚Ä¢	Purchase role:
	‚Ä¢	Cannot start inventories
	‚Ä¢	Can view inventory history (read-only)
	‚Ä¢	Business role:
	‚Ä¢	No access to inventory

‚∏ª

8) UX & design constraints
	‚Ä¢	Inventory workflow must be:
	‚Ä¢	Guided
	‚Ä¢	Step-by-step
	‚Ä¢	Easy to understand for non-technical users
	‚Ä¢	Scanning view must:
	‚Ä¢	Support long lists
	‚Ä¢	Be scrollable
	‚Ä¢	Clearly distinguish item states

Avoid:
	‚Ä¢	Complex tables
	‚Ä¢	Hidden actions
	‚Ä¢	Ambiguous statuses

‚∏ª

Expected result
	‚Ä¢	Inventories are easy to launch
	‚Ä¢	Scope is clearly defined
	‚Ä¢	Discrepancies are immediately visible
	‚Ä¢	Inventory freshness is visible per model
	‚Ä¢	Full audit trail is available via history

‚∏ª

Validation sentence

If a user cannot clearly see what was expected, what was found,
what is missing, and what should not have been there,
then the inventory feature is incomplete.

